{"author": "y_", "date": "2015-08-04 19:52", "post_id": "id1164048", "url": "https://4programmers.net/Forum/Kariera/233131-ile_zarabiacie?p=1164048#id1164048", "vote_count": "13", "post_content": "<div class=\"post-content\"><div><p>I'm going to leave some general information about the market in Krakow, based on information gathered from contact with recruiters over the past year or so. The ranges I have been seeing over the past year are from 9k - 18k gross for companies considered to be in the third \"basket\" as laid out by Junior_Krakow in this post: <a href=\"http://4programmers.net/Forum/Kariera/224406-widelki_na_roznych_poziomach_-_krakow_java?p=988146#id988146\">http://4programmers.net/Forum/Kariera/224406-widelki_na_roznych_poziomach_-_krakow_java?p=988146#id988146</a> - This means around 9k for entry level programmers and up to around 18k for team leads / senior specialists.</p>\n<p>Here are some of the numbers I have seen recruiters throw around in the past 6 months:</p>\n<p>Position | Technology | Company | Brackets | Form<br>\nJunior Developer | dotnet/C# | unnamed British bank | 9000-12000 gross | contracted or B2B<br>\nTeam Leader | dotnet/C# | unnamed British startup - online banking | 16000 gross | contracted<br>\nTechnical Leader | dotnet/C# | UBS Krakow | 14000-17000 gross | contracted<br>\nJunior Developer | PHP | unnamed Polish marketing company | 10000-12000 gross | contracted<br>\nSenior Platform Engineer | dotnet, java, server + middleware automation | GE Healthcare | around 20000 gross | contracted<br>\nJunior Sysadmin | server + middleware automation | Wikia | 11000-14000 gross | contracted<br>\nQuantitative Developer | C++/C#/R | unnamed Polish bank | around 14000 gross | contracted<br>\nDeveloper | dotnet/C# | unnamed Czech company | around 14000 gross | B2B<br>\nSenior Software Engineer | java | Allegro | 14000-18000 gross | contracted</p>\n<p>The market has changed drastically in the past 3 years. Many new companies have entered and consequently raised compensation requirements (This trend seems to continue into this year). Let's just hope this doesn't end with a bubble in a few years when the skill/cost ratio for Polish developers stops being attractive.</p>\n<p>Good luck :]</p>\n</div> <!----> <!----></div>"}
